{"questionId":"32706913","questionHtml":"<p>the equation of the perpendicular bisector of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>RS</mi><mo>]</mo></math>. Give your answer in the form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>11</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>6</mn></math><em><strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>finding negative reciprocal of their gradient<em><strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>m</mi><mo>⊥</mo></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac></math></strong></em></p>\n<p>attempt to substitute their midpoint and their gradient into equation of straight line&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>eg. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>23</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math> &nbsp; <strong>OR</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mo>(</mo><mn>11</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>167</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>92</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>166666</mn><mo>…</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>91666</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>59</mn><mn>12</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><em><strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note</strong>: Substituting <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math> (no negative reciprocal) and their point into the equation of straight line would receive at most <em><strong>A1M0M1A0</strong></em>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"32706913","referenceCode":"24N.2.SL.TZ1.1bii","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"the equation of the perpendicular bisector of [RS]. Give your answer in the form y=mx+c.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Prior learning","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.5—Intersection of lines, equations of perpendicular bisectors","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.6—Voronoi diagrams"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}